  "prompt": "What is the acceptable TDS level of drinking water?",
  "response": "The acceptable Total Dissolved Solids (TDS) level of drinking water can vary depending on local regulations and guidelines, but generally, the following ranges apply:\n\n- **Ideal**: Typically, the ideal TDS level for drinking water is below 300 milligrams per liter (mg/L).\n  \n- **Acceptable**: Most guidelines consider a TDS level of up to 500 mg/L to be acceptable for drinking water. The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) sets this as a secondary maximum contaminant level, which is non-enforceable but recommended for aesthetic considerations like taste.\n\n- **Upper Limit**: Some health organizations may suggest that TDS levels up to 1,000 mg/L can still be safe, although it might affect the taste and quality of the water.\n\nLevels above these might cause the water to taste salty or unpleasant, and they can indicate the presence of unwanted minerals or contaminants. It is always best to consult local water quality standards and guidelines for precise recommendations.",
